Part A. Introduction¶

In this minilab, we will use different machine learning classification algorithms such as Logistic Regression and Support Vector Machine. We carry over the Business Understanding and Data Preparation from Lab 1 to this Minilab. More information related to Visualization and Data Preprocessing can be found in Lab 1.

I. Business Understanding¶

Kaggle dataset (https://www.kaggle.com/stefanoleone992/fifa-20-complete-player-dataset) players_20.csv is used in this lab. The dataset provides detailed information of all the soccer players statistics in various clubs of major soccer leagues in the world. The data is originally from the FIFA soccer game created by EA sports. This game estimates the abilities of the actual players and built the game according to the data. And the Kaggle dataset is scraped from www.sofifa.com, where the gaming data is collected. The data we used is last updated on Sept 19th 2019.

The dataset is important because the abilities of players is estimated from the actual players. FIFA is a very popular game and EA Sports is one of the largest sport video game developer. The player abilities estimate is quite accurate. Therefore, useful knowledge can be mined from the data for analyzing variety problems in the soccer industry. For example, wage analysis, player analysis, training strategy, budget analysis, sport gambling strategy plan can be performed using this dataset. Soccer has been a big industry which the market size is estimated to worth $488 billion in 2018 according to the Business Wire.

Some of the analyses we are interested in to performs are:

  1. Run predictive model to predict wage from players abilities. We will select some features to run regression model. Also, we will try running PCA and regression model. To measure the effectiveness, we will use RMSE, MAE and R squared.

  2. Run classification model to classify players position from the players ability. To validate our model, we will use accuracy, precision, F1 score and ROC.

We also intent to use the detailed game statistics from fbref.com. We can potential run analysis using the win/lose results from the real time data.

This image helps us understand various positions that a soccer players is assigned during a game. The feature player_positions represents multiple positions that a player can play in with a comma seperate value, the very first item in that list has a preferred field position of the player. The team_position is the current positon that the player is being used in the team. For our analysis we will use the players preferred positon.

The statistics of each individual player ability in respective positons are in seperate features on a scale of 1 to 100 as described in the table output aboive.

A goal keeper does not occupy any of the positions that a regular player occupies under normal circumstances which means he will not have any specific statistics for those features. A goal keeper on the other hand has a different set of features to capture his statistics, these are displayed in the table above in the Variable_cat field as 'GK'.

I. Create Models¶

In this section, we create different logistic regression (LR) and support vector machine (SVM) models for the classification task involved with FIFA dataset and assess how well each model performs (use 80/20 training/testing split). We also adjust parameters of the models to make them more accurate. Although we have a mid size dataset, we also run the SGD model just to evaluate its time performance in converging to the minimum.

In our analysis, we are classifying players' position from the fifa dataset. Below, we make a copy of our cleaned dataset into players_X which includes all our regressor variables that we identified in Lab1. There are a total of 31 features including players mental, attacking, skills, movements, defending, power, height and weight attributes. The actual players' position are in players_y dataframe. We will scale all the features to zero mean and 1 Std Deviation into X_players_scaled and use this for our analysis.

# Adapted from:
# https://www.featureranking.com/tutorials/machine-learning-tutorials/information-gain-computation/
def gini_index(y):
    probs = pd.value_counts(y,normalize=True)
    return 1 - np.sum(np.square(probs))

def plot_class_dist(y):
    class_ct = len(np.unique(y['preferred_position_cat']))
    vc = pd.value_counts(y['preferred_position_cat'])
    print('Total Records', len(y['preferred_position_cat']))
    print('Total Classes:', class_ct)
    print('Class Gini Index', gini_index(y['preferred_position_cat']))
    print('Smallest Class Id:',vc.idxmin(),'Records:',vc.min())
    print('Largest Class Id:',vc.idxmax(),'Records:',vc.max())
    print('Accuracy when Guessing:', np.round( (1 / len(np.unique(y['preferred_position_cat']))) * 100, 2), '%')
    
    position_counts = pd.DataFrame(df_pred_pos['preferred_position_cat'].value_counts())
    position_counts['Percentage'] = position_counts['preferred_position_cat']/position_counts.sum()[0]
    print(position_counts)
    plt.figure(figsize=(4,4))
    plt.pie(position_counts['Percentage'],labels = ['DEF', 'FWD', 'MID', 'GK']);

We see some imbalance in the classifications, we keep it as is but we will try to evaluate various rebalance stratergies in Logistic regression to see if there is any impact on accuracy.
We prepare our test / train split using a 80/20 split. We chose to use StratifiedShufflesplit to ensures that there will be selection in similar proportion of classes from each group and omit sampling bias.

The common function below uses a grid searchCV scikitlearn api to evaluate a set of models that are passed to it. The best performing model is identified with the graphs show comparative statistics based on f-1 score. A confusion matrix is also displayed.

The evaluation is done as follows:
 model_name: string representing the model name can be anything
 params: List of model tuning paramters
 clf: the estimator classification to evaluate
 X_train, y_train: The scaled train dataset, the grid search will use this data set and run internal CV to evaluate the model passed
 X_test, y_test: this test data set is used for calculating confusion matrix on the best model estimated.
 nCV: Number of cross validation to run

Returns :
 modal_stats: a summary of best model

In [24]:
def evaluate_model_performance(model_name, params, clf, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, nCV = 10):
    ##Create a 70%/30% split using stratified shuffle split in order to maintain ration
    #grid = gridcv(clf, params, cv=3,scoring='f1_micro')
    # We prepare the grid search object
    grid = gridcv(clf, params, cv=nCV,scoring='accuracy', refit=True )
    grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
    model_stat =  pd.DataFrame()
    model_stat['model_name'] =[str(model_name)]

    res = grid.cv_results_

    #grid.cv_results_.keys()
    res.keys()
    res['params']
    grid_scr = pd.DataFrame()
    grid_scr['params'] = res['params']
    grid_scr['mean_test_score'] = res['mean_test_score']
    grid_scr = pd.DataFrame(grid_scr)
    #print(grid_scr)

    grid_scr.plot.bar(color='grey',figsize=(10,6))
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Params')
    plt.grid(color='blue', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5)
    plt.ylim(0.5,.95)

    print("Best parameters set found on development set:")
    print()
    print(grid.best_params_)
    #model_stat['score'] = [grid.best_score_]
    print()
    print("Grid scores on development set:")
    print()
    means = res['mean_test_score']
    stds = res['std_test_score']
    for mean, std, params in zip(means, stds, res['params']):
        print("%0.5f (+/-%0.03f) for %r"
              % (mean, std * 2, params))
    print()

    print("Detailed classification report:")
    print()
    print("The model is trained on the full development set.")
    print("The scores are computed on the full evaluation set.")
    print()
    #build CM using test/Train
    y_true, y_pred = y_test, grid.predict(X_test)
    #y_pred
    print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred, target_names=['DEF', 'FWD', 'GK','MID']))
    s = classification_report(y_true, y_pred, target_names=['DEF', 'FWD', 'GK','MID'])
    model_stat['CM'] = s
    plot_confusion_matrix(grid, X_test,y_test,cmap=plt.cm.Blues,values_format='d')
    model_stat['time_refit'] = [grid.refit_time_]
    model_stat['model_param'] = [str(grid.best_params_)]
    model_stat['weighted_f1_score']=round(f1_score(y_true, y_pred, average='weighted'),2)
    #model_stat['accuracy']=accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)
    plt.grid(b=None);
    print()
    return model_stat

We will use model_stats to hold each model statistics for final evaluation.

I.1. Logistic Regression using various sampling stratergies¶

Logistic regression is one of the most widely used algorithms for classification in the industry and easy to implement and perform very well on linearly separable classes. In this minilab, we will deal with multinomial logistic regression for 4 classes (DEF, FWD, MID, GK) to predict the probabilities of the these 4 outcomes by modeling the nominal outcome variables, in which the log odds of the outcomes are modeled as a linear combination of the predictor variables. Like binary logistic regression, multinomial logistic regression uses maximum likelihood estimation to evaluate the probability of categorical membership. This method has better statistical properties than the least square approach to estimate the unknown linear regression coefficients in linear regression models. Maximum likelihood is a very general approach that is used to fit many of the nonlinear models, especially in our case here with the logistic regression model. In fact, the least squares approach is a special case of maximum likelihood mathematically. Multinomial logistic regression is often considered an attractive analysis in the industry because we do not need normality, linearity, or homoscedasticity assumptions. In this subsection, we used following sampling stratergies to approach the logistic regression analysis.

  1. Original data
  2. Undersampling_1
  3. Undersampling_2
  4. Oversampling
  5. PCA

Below is a short summary of each dataset sampling approach. The detail model summary will be in part B (model advantage).

4. SMOTE: Synthetic Minority Over-sampling¶

SMOTE works by selecting examples that are close in the feature space, drawing a line between the examples in the feature space and drawing a new sample at a point along that line. Specifically, a random example from the minority class is first chosen. Then k of the nearest neighbors for that example are found (typically k=5). A randomly selected neighbor is chosen and a synthetic example is created at a randomly selected point between the two examples in feature space.
şş https://machinelearningmastery.com/smote-oversampling-for-imbalanced-classification/

We use Synthetic Minority Over-sampling to over sample all classes, except the majority.
Original data: DEF:7362, FWD:4588, MID:4292, GK:2036
The dataset is increased from 18,278 records to 29,448 with each class containing 7,362 records.

5. LR using PCA¶

We now use Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to perform the LR analysis. PCA is an unsupervised linear transformation technique for dimensionality reduction. It is a useful technique when we have a large number of correlated features in the dataset. It allows us to summarize the information with a smaller number of collectively representative variables.

In [34]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot_pca(X):
    # Perform PCA on the data to reduce the number of initial features 
    # and to remove correlations that are common between pixel features 
    pca = PCA(n_components=X.shape[1])
    pca.fit(X)

    # Inspect the explained variances to determine how many components to use  
    plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8))
    plt.plot(np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_))
    plt.xlabel('number of components')
    plt.ylabel('cumulative explained variance');
    print('Cumulative Explained variance at 200 components:',sum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_[0:199]) )

I.2. Stochastic Gradient Descent Classifier¶

Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) is a popular alternative to the batch gradient descent algorithm when we have a very large dataset that is not uncommon in many machine learning applications. It is an approximation of gradient descent but it can reach convergence much faster because of the more frequent weight updates and it also can be used in online learning. Although we have a mid sized dataset, we are running the SGD model just to evaluate its time performance in converging to the minimum.

The above summary table are the information we captured from the models we trained. The following are the data we captured:
 model_name: represent the various model we tested.
 CM: the detail statistics of each best model from the gridsearchCV.
 time_refit: the time the model tool to refit the best model in the run.
 model_param: The best model parameters in the model.
 weighted_f1_score

We have trained and refined our models in different ways. The following is the detail of how we evaluated our models. Since we have imbalanced classes, f1 score is a better metric to evaluate our models. We will use the f1 score to evaluate the machine learning models in this minilab. This score can be interpreted as a weighted average of the precision and recall where its best value is at 1 and its worst score is at 0. The relative contribution of precision and recall to the f1 score are equal. Here is the formula to show how the f1 score is calculated

f1 = 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall).

In the multi-class and multi-label case, for example, in our study, with 4 classes DEF, FWD, MID and GK, the overall f1 score is the average of the f1 score of each class with weighting depending on the average parameter.

We evaluated five logistic regression models, a stochastic gradient descent and two support vector machine models using gridsearchCV. The overall summary of the best performing model in each category is displayed above. The models were tested using 10 fold cross validation with different sampling strategies (Except in case of SVC-SMOTE we reduced to 5 fold CV due to its runtime).

Overally, we see that SVC using Synthetic Minority Over-sampling technique (SMOTE) gave us a really good f1 score of 92%. This overall f1 score is the average of f1 scores for 4 classes. In particular, we can also see that the f1 score from the confusion matrix for MID position was 85%, they are the hardest scores to improve, and in other model too. The downside of this models is the time it takes to refit the best model, but since it is a small dataset, it should not be an issue.

Logistic regression using SMOTE is the second best model with f1 score 87%. Followed with SVC model with original dataset, the f1 score of both are very close but logistic regression is faster.

III. Interpret Feature Importance¶

The following attribute weight the most in our logistic regression model using the original dataset:
mentality_interceptions, mentality_positioning, mentality_vision, attacking_crossing, attacking_short_passing, defending_marking, defending_standing_tackle, defending_sliding_tackle

These variables are more important because they are position specific variables. For example, a defending (DEF) player has a higher interception mentality, marking and tackling in general because the position focus on defending attacking players. A forward (FWD) player in general has a much higher vision mentality because he needs to focus on catch defending players' mistake and turn it to the opportunity to goal.

The following attribute weight are close to zero, which means they are less important to the logistic regression model:
mentality_penalties, power_shot_power, power_jumping, and height_cm

These variables are less important because they are not position specific variables. For example, player of each position can be a penalty kick specialist. And each position require certain kind of shot power and jumping skills to become a good player in all positions. Also, height is not an important factor to the position.

Below, we run the best performed logistic regression with original dataset from the previous analysis

Since we have a total of 31 features, we end up with 31 dimensions. In the above plots, we are comparing the support vectors against the original class boundary by one dimension at a time. Taking a look at a mentality_aggression, we see the support vectors increase the class boundary. But for mentality_positioning and mentality_composure, the support vectors converge due to closer class boundary. This is due to the fact that the support vector can only have one boundary.
Overall, it means that the instances chosen as support vectors always lie along the model / classes’ decision boundary. That is how the instances are selected.

Part C. Conclusion and Discussion¶

In conclusion, we have studied the LR, SGD and SVM classifcations using the FIFA 20 dataset. With respect to the faster training time, the candidates are LR and SGD algorithms based on their mathematical properties but with lower accuracy.

SVC-SMOTE gave us the best overal f1 score in this study. The downside of this model is the time it takes to refit the best model. But since it is a small dataset, it is not a big issue.

LR is a probabilistic classification model using the sigmoid function, whereas SVC are a more geometric approach that maximise the margins to each class. They are similar in the way that they both can divide the feature space with a decision boundary. It is safe to assume that when compared to LR models, the SVM models are creating a wider margin between classes and generalizing better. Also, based on the cross validation report of the models, we see the f1 score for SVM is higher.
